0.1 Cleaning the data


It is vital to ensure that our data is clean and correctly formatted prior to using it in building models.

From the below, it can be noted that our data has many zeros. This was due to a pre-processing error that added zeros in lieu of NAs. The code below therefore replaces all zeros with NAs and removes columns and rows with NAs greater than our threshold value of 10%. The remaining NAs are then replaced by a relevant value of measure of central tendency using the centralImputation() function from the DMwR2 package. 

y1.all[,-1][y1.all[,-1]==0] <- NA

threshold <- 0.25
y1.all <- y1.all[colSums(is.na(y1.all))/nrow(y1.all)<=threshold]
y1.all<- y1.all[complete.cases(y1.all) | rowSums(is.na(y1.all)) / ncol(y1.all) < threshold, ]
y1.all <- centralImputation(y1.all)

#Removing any numerical rows where the value is above 10000
y1.all <- y1.all%>%filter(across(where(is.numeric), ~ . <= 10000 & . >= -10000, .names = "tmp") %>% rowSums() == ncol(select(y1.all, where(is.numeric))))

0.2 Summary statistics


The quickest way to analyse our data is to run summary statistics so we can observe the mean, median, mode of our variables. Additionally, can also observe the distribution of our data through functions like skewness and kurtosis.
The below codes from base r, hmisc, and dplyr packages enable us to do just that. It can be seen that besides book value per share and the dependent variable, bankruptcy, all the other independent variables are positively skewed. Generally, the data also shows great peakedness or excessive kurtosis. An analysis of outliers and disaggregation of data by event i.e.whether a company is bankrupt or not will help to explain this observation in more detail.
Finally, the summary statistics reveals a startling range in the variables which among other things may represent the presence of outliers on both tails of the data and suggest that our data may consist of more than one mode. 

data_summary <- describe(y1.all)

1 Analysis

1.1 Principal Component Analysis

We use principal component analysis here to understand which most explains bankruptcy in companies. This one of four tools that will be used in this analysis to measure the importance of features in bankruptcy prediction. The other features are: random forest future importance, Boosting feature importance, and the Logit regression feature importance.


Removing the Industry Variable

2 Correlation Matrices

As noted by Wang, Ma, and Yang (2013) predictive models are not resistant to multicollinearity especially those that apply traditional statistical methods such as the EMS model and logistic regression. It is therefore essential to analyse the extent to which the variables used in the models vary together. 

y1.all[,-2]%>%pairs.panels()

correlation.data <- print(cor(y1.all, use= "complete.obs"))

3 Statistical Testing

All features in the dataset were tested for their statistical significance at one year leading to bankruptcy. The spearman correlation rho estimate was used to test the explanatory variable for significance. Cassim (2020) observed that the method employed to test data for statistical significance should be based on the inherent characteristics of the data being tested. For example, when data is assumed to be parametric, i.e.normally distributed, then the commonly used procedures such as t-tests provide reliable results (Cassim, 2020).

3.1 Testing for Normality

shapiro_results <- lapply(y1.all[,-1], shapiro.test)
shapiro.p_values <- sapply(shapiro_results, function(x) x$p.value)
shapiro.stat <- sapply(shapiro_results, function(x) x$statistic)

shapiro.data <- kable(cbind(shapiro.stat, shapiro.p_values), caption = "Shapiro-Test - H0: Data is normally distributed")

ad_results <- lapply(y1.all[,-1], ad.test)
ad.p_values <- sapply(ad_results, function(x) x$p.value)
ad.stat <- sapply(ad_results, function(x) x$statistic)

ad.data <- kable(cbind(ad.stat,ad.p_values), caption = "Anderson-Darling test - H0: Data is normally distributed")

3.2 Statistical Significance.

When the data is skewed and non-parametric, alternative methods like the Spearman correlation provides better results (Cassim, 2020). Based on two popular standard normality tests, Anderson-Darling test, and Shapiro-Wilk test, it was discovered that both datasets were nonparametric and therefore spearmans ranks correction was adopted as seen below.

4 Visualising Balance


Data Balance Visualisation
A crucial aspect of any machine learning and modelling venture requires understanding the distribution of the dataset(s) to be used. Balance is defined as the degree to which the classes or labels are fairly represented. The balance of a dataset has a singular impact on the accuracy and reliability of a machine learning model. While ideally, a 50-50 split is recommended, most researchers struggle to get data. Thus, literature accepts up to 30-70 class split as balanced.

  1. Boosting

Boosting involves training multiple models sequentially, and each subsequent model focuses on retraining on the instances that the previous models failed to learn and the results from each model are aggregated to form a final prediction (Hastie, Tibshirani & Friedman, 2009). Furthermore, like bagging, boosting can be used with a variety of different base models, including decision trees, linear regression, and logistic regression. Boosting can be used to improve the accuracy of a model, especially when there is high bias in the data. Bias is used in machine learning and statistics to mean the difference between the predicted and the actual value (Paweek, 2019). 

# Train Boosting model
boost_model <- gbm(Bankruptcy ~ ., data = train_data, n.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 10, shrinkage = 0.01, distribution = "bernoulli")

# Make predictions on test data

# Convert predictions to binary classification
boosting_predictions_binary <- ifelse(Boosting_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

  1. Bagging

Bagging is an ensemble learning method that stands for bootstrap aggregating, and it involves creating multiple models on bootstrap samples of the data and combining their results to make a prediction (Hastie, Tibshirani &Friedman, 2009). Bagging can be used with a variety of different base models, including decision trees, linear regression, and logistic regression (Breimann, 1996). Bagging can improve the accuracy and robustness of a model, especially when there is high variance in the data (Breimann, 1996). 

# Train Bagging model

  1. Support Vector Machines

Support Vector Machines, or SVMs, are a widely used machine learning model, particularly for classification tasks. SVMs work by finding the hyperplane that separates the data into different classes with the maximum margin (Hua et al., 2007). The main advantage of SVMs is their ability to handle high-dimensional datasets and produce accurate predictions (Pal et al., 2016; Hua et al., 2007; & Mitchell, 1997). They are also very good at handling datasets with complex boundaries between classes (Hua et al., 2007). Furthermore, SVMs are resistant to overfitting, which is a common problem in machine learning.

  1. k- Nearest Neighbours

KNN is a type of lazy learning algorithm, meaning that it does not learn a model from the training data, but rather it memorises all the training data points and uses them to make predictions (Alpaydin, 2010). The KNN algorithm works by finding the K-nearest neighbours to a given data point in the training set and using their labels to make a prediction for that data point (Alpaydin, 2010). The value of K refers to the number of neighbours that the model should look, and larger values of K tend to produce smoother decision boundaries, while smaller values of K can lead to overfitting.

convert_to_percentage <- function(data) {
  if (!is.data.frame(data)) {
    stop("Input data must be a data frame.")
  }
  for (col in names(data)) {
    if (is.numeric(data[[col]])) {
      total <- sum(data[[col]])
      data[[col]] <- (data[[col]] / total) * 100
    } else {
      warning(paste("Column '", col, "' is not numeric. Skipping..."))
    }
  }
  
  return(data)
}

6 Comparison Between Raw_data and Ratio_data Accuracies

In this section we compare the performance of models when trained and tested on ratio financial data versus when trained and tested on raw financial data.

It is very evident that models predict with better accuracies when trained on ratio data than on unmodified financial data. Theres an stark difference of about 20% in predictive accuracy when models get trained using ratio data. This confirms a common accounting and finance belief that financial ratios have more informational power compared to raw financial data.

7 DE Long Test

The De Long test calculates the difference in the area under the ROC curve (AUC) between two classifiers and uses this difference to construct a z-statistic and calculate a p-value. The null hypothesis for the De Long test is that the AUCs of the two classifiers are equal, and the alternative hypothesis is that they are not equal. This paper used the logistic regression classifier as the benchmark. Furthermore, the models were then ranked based on how much they outperformed the logit classifier. Based on this criterion, the De Long test ranked the models as follows, from best to least best: bagging, random forest, logistic regression, kNN, gradient boosting, SVM, and ANN.

#RANDOM FOREST
# Define a function to compute the difference in AUCs between two models
a1.auc_diff.rf <- function(data, indices) {
  a1.rf.roc.resample <- roc(RF_ensemble_pred_binary[indices], test_data$Bankruptcy[indices])
  a1.lr.roc.resample <- roc(LR_predictions_binary[indices], test_data$Bankruptcy[indices])
  a1.auc_diff.rf <- auc(a1.lr.roc.resample) - auc(a1.rf.roc.resample)
  return(a1.auc_diff.rf)
}

# Perform bootstrapping to compare the two models
a1.results.rf <- boot(data = seq(LR_predictions_binary), statistic = a1.auc_diff.rf, R = 300)#Used 3000 but it is extremely slow on some laptops

# Print the bootstrapped confidence interval
a1.rf.ci <- boot.ci(a1.results.rf, type = "bca")

7.1 Brier Score

To measure the goodness of fit of the models, two main metrics have been applied: the brier score (BS), and AUCs of the models (already considered previously) when tested on training data (in-sample performance) and on test data (out-of-sample performance). Briefly, the brier score is the mean squared difference between the predicted probabilities and the actual outcomes (Pal et al., 2016). The brier score is analogous to the mean squared error (MSE) in regression algorithms. 

#OUT of SAMPLE
a1.results <- data.frame(cbind(Actual = test_data[,1], RF = RF_ensemble_pred,Boosting = Boosting_predictions, Bagging = Bagging_predictions, SVM = SVM_predictions, ANN = unlist(ANN_predictions[["net.result"]]),kNN = as.numeric(levels(knn_model))[knn_model], LR = LR_probabilities))

a1.brier_scores <- apply(a1.results[,-1], 2, function(x) mean((a1.results[,1] - x)^2))

a1.BS.AUC <- round(cbind(a1.auc.combo,a1.brier_scores),3)
